==English==

===Etymology===
Attributed to the poet {{w|Edmund Spenser}} in a conversation with Queen Elizabeth I <ref>Wikipedia page for Edmund Spenser, {{w|Edmund_Spenser#Rhyme_and_reason|''Rhyme and reason''}} topic</ref>. Translation from {{etyl|frm|en}} ''n'y avoir ryme ne raison'' ({{w|Eustache Deschamps}}).

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} {{l|en|[[logic|Logic]]; [[common sense]].}}
#: ''Prices vary considerably from one town to another with no apparent '''rhyme or reason'''.''
#: ''He would often fly into an unexpected rage without '''rhyme or reason'''.''

====Usage notes====
* Almost always used in a negative form, particularly with {{m|en|no}} and {{m|en|without}}.

